  <chunk id="56b2d409fd554bd2694eb7d938fd44fc282fd484.c3" text="Recently, the presence of G4s in viruses and their involvement in virus key steps has been provided 14 . G4s have been implicated in pathogenic mechanisms of the human immunodeficiency virus, where functionally significant G4s have been identified 5, 11, 15-17 and stabilized by G4 ligands with consequent antiviral effects 5, 18, 19 . G4s have been reported in the SARS coronavirus 20 , the human papilloma, Zika, Ebola and hepatitis C virus genome 21-24 . Among herpesviruses, RNA G4s have been implicated in the regulation of DNA replication and translation of the Epstein-Barr virus 25, 26 . We have shown that the herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) possesses several repeats of important G4-forming sequences, which could be stabilized by a G4 ligand with inhibition of viral DNA replication 27 . In addition, HSV-1 G4s, visualized with the aid of a G4-specific antibody in infected cells 12 , were shown to form massively in the cell nucleus, peak during viral replication and localize according to the viral genome intracellular movements 28 .">
